Iona College has retained Langan Engineering and Environmental Services to prepare a traffic
impact study for the proposed development of a mixed use residence hall that will provide a
total of 316 student housing beds and 6,790 sf of retail space.
The project site is located in the northwest corner of the North Avenue and Summit
Avenue/Iona College Main Entrance (S. Path) intersection on the west side of the college
campus. The property was previously developed and occupied by the Mirage Diner. Access to
the property is proposed to be provided via two driveways. The first, a full movement
driveway, will be accessed via Summit Avenue. The second, an exit only driveway, will be
located on White Oak Street, which is a one-way street in the northbound direction. The
existing access driveways along North Avenue providing access to the Diner parking lot will be
eliminated. The driveways provide access to a 39 space parking lot located behind the
proposed residence hall. It is proposed that the parking lot be utilized by retail patrons only.
The occupants of the proposed residence hall will utilize the existing parking located on the
It is noted that the property is currently developed and operated with a restaurant use. As such,
traffic is currently being generated from the project site. Further, the addition of the residence
hall will likely reduce commuter traffic traveling to/ from the campus. Accordingly, while we do
not expect a significant increase in traffic to be generated by the proposed project given the
elimination of the Diner and reduction in commuter traffic, to be conservative, we have
prepared this traffic study with the assumption that the proposed retail and residence hall will
generate new traffic demands to the campus. Accordingly, we estimated the number of trips
the proposed development would generate based on data compiled for Land Use 820
(Shopping Center) by the Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) as contained in Trip
edition. Further, we estimated the number of trips for the proposed residence
hall based on data compiled for student housing apartment buildings in a Trip Generation Study
conducted by Spack Consulting dated April 12, 2012. Based upon these data sources, we
estimate that the development will generate approximately 44 new trips (23 enter, 21 exit)
during the weekday morning peak hour and 116 new trips (58 enter, 58 exit) during the
We determined the directional distribution of the retail and residential site-generated trips
based on an examination of demographic data and existing travel patterns in the study area.

Based on a review of the analyses, we do not expect the proposed development to significantly
impact the adjacent roadway network during peak traffic hours. It is determined that the
adjacent roadway network has sufficient capacity to accommodate the traffic generated by the
project. The elimination of the existing Diner curb cuts along North Avenue will reduce points
of conflict along this arterial roadway and improve vehicular and pedestrian safety. The
additional pedestrian traffic that the proposed residence hall will create on the crosswalks on
North Avenue is not expected to have a significant impact on the traffic operations at the
Summit Avenue and Iona College main entrance intersection, which is expected to continue to
operate at acceptable levels of service.

Eastchester Road intersects North Avenue to form a three-leg signalized intersection. The
eastbound Eastchester Road approach provides a left-turn lane and a channelized right-turn
lane. The northbound North Avenue approach provides a left-turn lane and two thru lanes. The
southbound North Avenue approach provides a shared thru/right-turn lane and a thru lane. The
signal operates under three phases with a 110-second cycle length. The signalized
intersections in the study area along North Avenue operate as part of a coordinated system
each with an offset of zero. Under the coordinated system the North Avenue R.O.W. phase at
each intersection changes to display red at the same time. Pedestrian crosswalks are provided
along the eastbound approach and the northbound approach.

To examine traffic and pedestrian conditions near the site, manual turning movement traffic
counts were conducted during the morning and evening peak periods on a typical weekday at
the study intersections. Specifically, manual turning movement counts were conducted on
Tuesday, 29 April 2014. Pedestrian counts were also conducted for each intersection in the
study area on the same day as the traffic counts.
Based upon the traffic counts, we establish peak hour traffic volumes at the study locations.
The manual traffic counts identify distinct times during the weekday morning and evening
when traffic experienced its highest levels. According to the manual traffic count data
collected, the weekday morning peak hour generally occurs from 7:45 AM to 8:45 AM; and the
weekday evening peak hour occurs from 3:00 PM to 4:00 PM. The pedestrian volume peak
hour was observed to occur from 9:00 AM to 10:00 AM during the weekday morning peak
period; and from 3:00 PM to 4:00 PM during the weekday evening peak period.
To verify the data, we reviewed previous traffic count data collected by TRC Engineers, Inc. in
2010/2011 and published in a prior traffic report for the campus prepared by VHB, Engineering,
Surveying and Landscape Architecture, P.C. The prior data is consistent with the data collected
in 2014 and it was determined that the collected traffic volumes and pedestrian data provide a
representative sampling of weekday peak hour traffic conditions on the adjacent roadway

This section of the report covers background traffic growth, site-generated trips, trip distribution
and future traffic volumes. We anticipate the proposed development will be complete by the
end of 2017. Accordingly, we projected traffic volumes to include existing traffic and new
traffic created by background growth to derive the 2017 No-Build traffic volumes. We then
added site-generated trips to the 2017 No-Build traffic volumes to derive the 2017 Build traffic
We increased the existing peak hour traffic volumes by a compounded annual growth rate of
1.00 percent, to derive the 2017 No-Build traffic volumes. We applied a conservative factor to
the traffic volumes as compared to the forecasted growth rate factor, for North Avenue, of
0.10% as established by the NYSDOT (New York State Department of Transportation) for
Westchester County. Figure 4 shows the 2017 No-Build traffic volumes.
We prepared trip generation estimates for the proposed development using data compiled for
Land Use 820 (Shopping Center) by the Institute of Transportation Engineers as contained in
edition. Additionally, we estimated the number of trips for the proposed
residence hall based on data compiled for student housing apartment buildings in a Trip
Generation Study conducted by Spack Consulting dated April 12, 2012.
The basic principle of the ITE Trip Generation data is that the data was collected at single-use,
free-standing sites. However, this development will have a mix of uses that will interact with
each other. As a result, the total vehicle trips generated by the development will be reduced
from the sum of the individual uses. This reduction of total vehicle trips generated is defined as
internal capture. However, to provide a conservative analysis, we did not account for internal
A certain percentage of traffic attracted to retail land uses generally relates to the volume of
traffic passing by a site. These trips are diverted into a site from the adjacent passing travel
stream and continue along their original trip path when exiting a site. These specified trips are
known as “pass-by” trips and are not new to an area.
For purposes of this analysis we utilized a pass-by percentage of 25% for the retail use of the
proposed development. The pass-by percentage was applied to retail site generated trips for
both the weekday morning and evening peak hour. Table 1 summarizes the trip generation
estimates. Figure 5 shows the pass-by trips and distributions.

Pedestrian traffic is an important factor on any college campus and with the development of a
new residence hall it is an element that needs to be considered when analyzing the
developments impact on the surrounding area. On a college campus a significant volume of
pedestrian traffic is expected to be associated with a residence hall land use. As such it would
be expected that completion of the proposed residence hall at Iona College would result in an
increase to the pedestrian traffic crossing North Avenue to/from the main campus of Iona
We incorporated the existing pedestrian counts that were conducted at each intersection into
our analyses to determine the impact pedestrian traffic has at each intersection. More
specifically we looked at the intersection of North Avenue and Summit Avenue/Iona College
main entrance and observed 353 pedestrian utilizing the crosswalks along the north/south leg,
North Avenue, approaches during the weekday morning peak hour and 442 pedestrians utilizing
the crosswalk during the weekday evening peak hour. It is noted that a majority of the
pedestrian traffic is utilizing the crosswalk along the south leg, North Avenue, approach due to
the location of the existing residence halls being on the south side of Summit Avenue.
Additionally, we obtained data from Iona College on the number of beds contained in the three
existing residence halls located on the west side of North Avenue in the southwest corner of
the North Avenue and Summit Avenue/Iona College main entrance intersection. The
information provided to us included the following:
Utilizing the pedestrian count data and the total number of existing beds on the west side of
North Avenue we calculated an existing rate for the number of pedestrians per bed. The
calculated rate for the weekday morning peak hour is 0.409 pedestrians per bed and the
weekday evening peak hour is 0.512 pedestrians per bed. Based on the calculated rates the
proposed 316 bed residence hall is expected to generate 129 new pedestrians during the
weekday morning peak hour and 162 new pedestrians during the weekday evening peak hour.
An advantage of the proposed residence hall being located on the north side on Summit
Avenue is that the additional pedestrian volume would be expected to utilize the crosswalk
located along the north leg, North Avenue, approach. Figure 13 illustrates the 2017 Build
weekday morning and evening peak hour pedestrian volumes.
This section describes the capacity analysis we conducted to assess traffic operations for the
No-Build and Build conditions. Capacity analysis provides an indication of the adequacy of road
Level of Service (LOS) is the term used to denote different operating conditions that occur on a
given road segment under various traffic volume demands. LOS is a qualitative measure that
considers a number of factors including road geometry, speed, travel delay and freedom to
maneuver. LOS designations range from A to F and provide an index of operational qualities of
a road segment or an intersection. LOS A represents the best operating conditions; LOS F
LOS designations are reported differently for signalized and unsignalized intersections. For
signalized intersections, the analysis considers the operation of all traffic entering the
intersection. For unsignalized intersections, the analysis considers the operation of all
movements that conflict with other movements, such as main-line left turns and traffic exiting a
side street. The evaluation criteria used to analyze the study area intersections are based on
the 2010 Highway Capacity Manual (HCM), published by the Transportation Research Board
and the latest version of the Synchro software.

level between 9:00 AM and 6:00 PM. After 6:00 PM, the volume begins to decrease in the
lots, this is apparent in the counts conducted during the Tuesday survey. The campus reaches
its peak occupancy at 72% at 11:00 AM.
The figure below displays the exiting parking accumulation in graphical form for all the occupied
parking spaces on campus combined and organized by summary of lots. The individual lot
accumulation count tables are included in Appendix E.
In accordance with the aforementioned section the total existing supply of parking available on
the Iona College campus is 1287 parking spaces. The overall peak parking demand was
observed to occur at 11:00 AM when the campus reached 72% occupancy with a total of 891
spaces occupied out of 1242 parking spaces in the main campus parking lots (Note: does not
include Lots E, N, and P).

part time faculty members, 392 full time employees, 65 part time employees, 1,738 students
not residing on campus (commuter students), an occupancy count of 1,200 for the Athletic
Facilities, and 1,372 students residing on campus. The required parking for the existing
campus is 1,111 parking spaces resulting in a surplus of 176 parking spaces. This calculated
parking requirement is consistent with the data obtained in the parking survey in April 2014

Langan finds that the proposed project will not significantly impact operations in the study area
during peak hours. Moreover, the proposed site access driveways are expected to operate
acceptably during the peak hours. It is noted that the results of this analyses are conservative
in its findings based upon the following:
The project site is currently active and generating traffic associated with the Mirage
Diner. No credit was taken in our analyses for the removal of that use from the property.
The proposed residence hall will likely reduce peak hour commuter traffic traveling to
The proposed mixed use nature of the building will likely result in a substantial portion of
the new retail space patrons being drawn from the campus student population, and may
not increase traffic demands as projected herein, No credit has been taken in our traffic
projections and analyses for the potential capture of the retail patrons from the existing
The elimination of the existing curb cuts along North Avenue will improve traffic and
pedestrian safety along this section of North Avenue.
The additional pedestrian traffic on the north leg, North Avenue, approach associated with the
proposed residence hall development is not expected to impact traffic operations at main Iona
College entrance intersection. The aforementioned intersection is expected to continue to
operate at acceptable levels of service. It is noted that overall the pedestrian traffic in the study
area does not appear to have a significant impact on the areas traffic operations. The existing
signal phasing at the study intersections provide adequate green time to accommodate both
the traffic and pedestrian volumes utilizing the various intersections.
